[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm looking into how function literals work in Scala 3. It seems that if I have a typed parameter within braces, I need to include parentheses around it, like this: `{ (featureKey: FeatureKey) => ... }`. It’s interesting that in Scala 2, single typed parameters could be valid without parentheses, but that doesn’t seem to apply here. Maybe the error I'm seeing is because `featureKey: FeatureKey =>` is being treated as type ascription. I also noted that public top-level classes don't necessarily require the public keyword in Scala.
